VTwo months ago, my kids and I huddled around a cell phone
p4
aVwatching the live stream of the Game Awards,
p5
aVone of the video game industry's biggest nights.
p6
aVThey announced the nominees for the Game for Impact,
p7
aVan award that's given to a thought-provoking video game
p8
aVwith a profound prosocial message or meaning.
p9
aVThey opened the envelope
p10
aVand they read the title of our video game.
p11
aVAn award ...
p12
aVfor impact.
p13
aVIt was almost funny, actually,
p14
aVbecause I always thought that winning an award like that
p15
aVwould have this huge impact on my life,
p16
aVbut I found that the opposite is true.
p17
aa(lp18
VThe big nights,
p19
aVthe accomplishments \u2014
p20
aVthey fade.
p21
aVBut the hardest nights of my life have stuck with me,
p22
aVimpacting who I am
p23
aVand what I do.
p24
aa(lp25
VIn 2010, my third son, Joel, was diagnosed with a rare and aggressive brain tumor.
p26
aVAnd before that year was finished,
p27
aVdoctors sat my husband and I down
p28
aVand let us know that his tumor had returned
p29
aVdespite the most aggressive chemotherapy and radiation that they could offer him.
p30
aVOn that terrible night,
p31
aVafter learning that Joel had perhaps four months to live,
p32
aVI cuddled up with my two older sons in bed \u2014
p33
aVthey were five and three at the time \u2014
p34
aVand I never really knew how much they understood,
p35
aVso I started telling them a bedtime story.
p36
aVI told them about this very brave knight named Joel
p37
aVand his adventure fighting a terrible dragon called cancer.
p38
aVEvery night, I told them more of the story,
p39
aVbut I never let the story end.
p40
aVI was just building up a context that they could understand
p41
aVand hoping that our prayers would be answered
p42
aVand I would never have to tell them that that knight,
p43
aVwho had fought so bravely,
p44
aVwas done fighting
p45
aVand could rest now, forever.
p46
aa(lp47
VFortunately, I never did have to finish that bedtime story.
p48
aVMy children outgrew it.
p49
aVJoel responded better than anyone expected to palliative treatment,
p50
aVand so instead of months,
p51
aVwe spent years learning how to love our dying child with all of our hearts.
p52
aVLearning to recognize that shameful feeling
p53
aVof holding back just a little love
p54
aVto try to spare ourselves just a little pain
p55
aVsomewhere further down the road.
p56
aVWe pushed past that self-preservation
p57
aVbecause Joel was worth loving even if that love could crush us.
p58
aVAnd that lesson of intense vulnerability has changed me ...
p59
aVmore than any award ever could.
p60
aa(lp61
VWe started living like Joel could live,
p62
aVand we began developing a video game called "That Dragon, Cancer."
p63
aVIt was the story of Joel.
p64
aVIt was the story of hope in the shadow of death.
p65
aVIt was the story of faith
p66
aVand doubt,
p67
aVand the realization that a wrestle with doubt is a part of faith \u2014
p68
aVmaybe the biggest part of it.
p69
aVIt was a story that began as a miracle
p70
aVand ended as a memorial.
